In order to find $a'(t_0)$ we need to find $b(t_0)$. Using the Pythagorean theorem and the fact that $a(t_0)=3$ and $c=5$, we can find that $b(t_0)=4$.


Let's plug $\blueD{b(t_0)}=\blueD{4}$, $\maroonD{b'(t_0)}=\maroonD{6}$, and $\goldD{a(t_0)}=\goldD{3}$ into the expression for $a'(t_0)$:

$\begin{align}
a'(t_0)&=-\dfrac{\blueD{b(t_0)}\maroonD{b'(t_0)}}{\goldD{a(t_0)}}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{(\blueD{4})(\maroonD{6})}{(\goldD{3})}
\\\\
&=-8
\end{align}$

Now let's plug $\blueD{b(t_0)}=\blueD{4}$, $\maroonD{b'(t_0)}=\maroonD{6}$, $\goldD{a(t_0)}=\goldD{3}$, and $\purpleC{a'(t_0)}=\purpleC{-8}$ into the expression for $A'(t_0)$:

$\begin{align}
A'(t_0)&=\dfrac{\purpleC{a'(t_0)}\blueD{b(t_0)}+\goldD{a(t_0)}\maroonD{b'(t_0)}}{2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{(\purpleC{-8})(\blueD{4})+(\goldD{3})(\maroonD{6})}{2}
\\\\
&=-7
\end{align}$

